passages.text: Updated Model w/ 2026/20 27 FFO Up, Though Still Below Street; JVs/Development Are Swing Factors

We updated our BDN model and made NAREIT FFO/share revisions both downward and upward. Our 2025 NAREIT FFO/share estimate is down from \(\) 0.62\(to\) \ \(0.60\) (- 29.3% y/y), which compares to Bloomberg consensus of \(\) 0.62\(and sits at the low end of the 2Q25 updated guidance (range of\) \ \(0.60 - 0.66\) ). Recall that BDN updated its 2025 FFO guidance with its 2Q25 earnings release and removed land sale gains (was\) \ \(5\) million or \(\) 0.03\(share at the midpoint in previous guidance). Taking this out drove the reduction in our numbers, offset by a little stronger NOI run rate from the quarter.

For 2026, our FFO/share estimate is up from \(\) 0.62\(to\) \ \(0.64\) (+7.2% y/y), which compares to Bloomberg consensus of \(\) 0.69\(. Our 2027 FFO/share estimate is up from\) \ \(0.63\) to \(\) 0.66\((+2.4\% y / y),\) which compares to Bloomberg consensus of \(\) 0.73\(. The upward revisions in 2026 and 2027 are a function of the aforementioned better NOI run rate coming out of 2Q compared to our prior model. On the negative side, we still think Street numbers have room to come down some, as drags from the company's developments and timing of lease commencements are notable. But on the positive side, the restructuring of some of its joint ventures (i.e., refinancing debt) should be helpful to reported NAREIT FFO/share; we assume three JVs being recapped in 1Q26 (details below).

Overall, we think there is still some variability in BDN's earnings over the next couple of years depending on how lease- up at its developments, non- core sales, and JV refinancings play out. But our view is that the substantial downward estimate revisions that have been seen in the last year (2025 FFO/share consensus going from \(\) 0.96\(to\) \ \(0.62\) and 2026 going from \(\) 1.06\(to\) \ \(0.69\) ) should be done.

Assuming an \(8.9\%\) blended cap rate, we arrive at our NAV/share estimate of \(\) 6\(. At its current stock price, we calculate an implied cap rate of\) 9.6\% \(. Using our DCF model (2% long - term AFFO growth rate, 12% equity discount), we arrive at our 2026 year - end price target of\) \ \(5\) /share. At its current stock price, we calculate an implied 2026 FFO and AFFO multiples of 6.7x and 15.7x, respectively. Although we do think this discounted valuation level is on trough earnings and there could be some re- rating upward if greater visibility on a return to growth ensues, the risk level is still high. We thus continue to rate shares Neutral. Some near- to- intermediate term items to watch include the lease- up of development, JV recaps, the new added hotel development, the forthcoming IBM move- out in Austin, and the potential for a dividend cut to preserve liquidity. The following goes through the Pkey assumptions in our model.

Core occupancy: We assume 2025 year- end core occupancy to be \(89.0\%\) which is up 40bps from 2Q25's \(88.6\%\) and at the high end of the company's guidance range of \(88 - 89\%\) . We assume occupancy to grow another 100bps in 2026 and end at \(90.0\%\) , and we expect it to lose 320bps in 2027 and end at \(86.8\%\) . Recall \(\sim 596k\) sf (about 500bps of occupancy) leased to IBM in Austin

We maintain our Neutral rating on BDN. The company's occupancy and rents have held up arguably better than other office REITs since the pandemic. While this relative picture has been encouraging, it has faced other challenges, such as slower development leasing, higher capital costs, and a leveraged balance sheet. Earnings should be around trough levels, but there remains wood to chop with regards to refinancing joint ventures, addressing future large move- outs (i.e., IBM), and setting a sustainable dividend that allows for optimal cash retention.

BDN trades at 6.7x our 2026 FFO estimate vs. the office REIT group average of 10.9x and 15.7x our 2026 AFFO estimate vs. the office REIT group average of 22.8x. Excluding leverage, we calculate that BDN trades at 11.7x EV/EBITDA vs. the office peer average of 14.0x. Using a \(8.9\%\) blended cap rate, we estimate its NAV/share to be \(6. At its current stock price, we calculate an implied cap rate of \(9.6\%\) . Further, BDN's dividend yield of \(14.1\%\) is higher than its peer average of \(5.1\%\) .
is a known move- out event in 2027; we assume the rest of the portfolio to gain 180bps occupancy in 2027.

- Rent spreads: We assume rent spreads to be \(-1.8\% / + 4.3\%\) on cash/GAAP basis for 2025, which compares to guidance of \(-1.75\% / + 4.0\%\) at the midpoint. We assume cash/GAAP rent spreads to be \(-1\% / + 6\%\) for 2026 and flat/ \(+8\%\) for 2027.

- JV recaps: We assume BDN to complete recaps for 3025 JFK – Residential, 3025 JFK – Commercial, and One Uptown – Residential in 1Q26, as they all should reach stabilization by then. We go over the details on each project below (and more in our “Recap Math” tab in the model), but we calculate that these recaps will help FFO by \(\sim 4\%\) on annual basis.
3025 JFK – Residential:

- Valuation at recap and BDN's proceeds: We assume stabilized annual NOI to be \(11 million ($325 million budget x 6.8\% yield x residential being 50\% of the project) and valued at a 5.5\% cap rate to get to asset value of\)201 million. Given prefs to be \(\sim \$33\) million and debt to be \(\sim \$93\) million, we assume BDN to get \(\sim \$75\) million of net proceeds back on this project for all of its equity stake.

- New capital stack and BDN's holding in new structure: We assume 60\% LTV on the \(201 million valuation or\)120.5 million for a permanent financing mortgage with a 5.5\% rate and the rest being common equity. We assume BDN to keep a 10\% equity stake, hence needing to put nearly \$10 million of cash back into the new JV vehicle.
3025 JFK – Commercial:

- Valuation at recap and BDN's proceeds: We assume stabilized annual NOI to be \(11 million (\)325 million budget x 6.8\% yield x commercial being 50\% of the project) and valued at a 7.5\% cap rate to get to asset value of \$147 million. Given prefs to be \(\sim \$33\) million and debt to be \(\sim \$93\) million, we assume BDN to get \(\sim \$21\) million in net proceeds back on this project for all of its equity stake.

- New capital stack and BDN's holding in new structure: We assume 55\% LTV on the \$147 million valuation or \$81 million for a permanent financing mortgage with a 6.5\% rate and the rest being common equity. We assume BDN to keep a 10\% equity stake, hence needing to put nearly \$7 million of cash back into the new JV vehicle.
One Uptown – Residential:

- Valuation at recap and BDN's proceeds: We assume stabilized annual NOI to be \$7 million (\)144 million budget x 5\% yield) and valued at a 5.5\% cap rate to get to asset value of \$131 million. Given prefs to be \(\sim \$38\) million and debt to be \$85 million, we assume BDN to get \(\sim \$8\) million of net proceeds back on this project for all of its equity stake.  
- New capital stack and BDN's holding in new structure: We assume 60\% LTV on the \$131 million valuation or \$78.6 million for a permanent financing mortgage with a 5.5\% rate and the rest being common equity. We assume BDN to keep a 10\% equity stake, hence needing to put about \$5 million of cash back into the new JV vehicle.

We are establishing our 2026 year- end price target of \(\) 5\(/share. Our price target is based on a DCF model. For "cash flow," we use dividends derived from our earnings model through 2031, thereafter assuming a long- term AFFO growth rate of\) 2.0\% \(and\) 100\% \(AFFO payout ratio. Our\) 2.00\% \(long- term growth rate assumes\) 1.0- 1.25\% \(core NOI growth, leveraged to\) 1.25- 1.5\% \(bottom- line growth, and\) 50- 75 \$bps of contribution from development projects and re- investing proceeds from asset dispositions. We assume a\) 12\% \(discount rate, which is higher than peers.
